long_desc.thetext:
HEAD after fix for bug 366063

Since @NonNullByDefault is no longer propogated to all enclosed elements, the following case is broken:

(Have X on Y's build path)

Project X
--------------
@NonNullByDefault
class X{
    public void foo(Object o) {}
}

Project Y
--------------
class Y {
    public void yfoo() {
         new X().foo(null);   // No warning here
    }
}

(In reply to comment #12)
> (In reply to comment #9)
> > (2) Thanks for handling annotations on enclosing types, which my patch missed.
> > However, what happens if binaryBinding.enclosingType is an
> > UnresolvedReferenceBinding? I'm afraid we'd need to use
> > binaryBinding.enclosingType() which spoils lazy resolving for projects that use
> > null annotations. Or is that scenario unreachable in the first place?
> Hmm, good point. Though given that an enclosed type will be built only after
> the enclosing, I don't know if an Unresolved binding can come here. How do I
> test this case?

When trying to create an example most ways of referring to a binary type proved to run a loop left-to-right which ensures outers are resolved before inners.

The closest I could come to breaking our assumption was:

Put this into a jar:
  @NonNullByDefault class Outer {
      static inner class Inner {  
           public void bar(Object o) {} // default should apply
      }
  }
  public class Public extends Outer.Inner {}

Access this from source like this
  void trigger1(Public o) {
	o.bar(null);
  }

Here lookup of bar() indeed manages to resolve Inner before Outer is resolved!
We're still lucky(!) because of this snippet in the constructor of BinaryTypeBinding:
  	if (enclosingTypeName != null) {
		// attempt to find the enclosing type if it exists in the cache (otherwise - resolve it when requested)
		this.enclosingType = environment.getTypeFromConstantPoolName(enclosingTypeName, 0, -1, true, null /* could not be missing */); // pretend parameterized to avoid raw
		this.tagBits |= TagBits.MemberTypeMask;   // must be a member type not a top-level or local type
		this.tagBits |= TagBits.HasUnresolvedEnclosingType;
		if (enclosingType().isStrictfp())
			this.modifiers |= ClassFileConstants.AccStrictfp;
		if (enclosingType().isDeprecated())
			this.modifiers |= ExtraCompilerModifiers.AccDeprecatedImplicitly;
	}

this fetches from the environment the yet unresolved enclosing type and only via a side effect of calling enclosingType() this type is resolved!!!

So our assumption is correct: we never get a resolved inner with an unresolved outer, but I doubt that this is fully by design. ;P
